South African comedian Trevor Noah continues to set trends as a friend of the millennials even outside the US with the amazing work he has been doing with The Daily Show.Apart from recently launching his book Born a Crime: Stories from a South African Childhood and speaking out against racism, the Johannesburg-born comedian has kept SA viewers entertained on social media platforms such as YouTube.His snippet of The Daily Show poking fun at President Jacob Zuma in the South African President Jacob Zuma &amp; The Panama Papers video clip was one of 2016 s most watched videos by South Africans with more than 2 million views.This bit of news was revealed by YouTube, which released its annual Rewind, looking back at the most-watched videos for the year globally and in South Africa.Adele Carpool Karaoke racked up a whopping 135 million views, making it the most watched YouTube video globally for 2016.Asian viral hit Piko Taro came in second with 93 million views for Pen-Pineapple-Apple-Pen/Piko-Taro and Utah-based father and son duo Daniel and Lincoln Markham s explanation of What s Inside a Rattlesnake Rattle? was third with 59 million views.These statistics are said to be based on views, shares, comments, likes and other qualifying criteria as calculated by YouTube.As far as the most watched music videos in the country is concerned, Rihanna and Drake topped the list with their hit track Work. Locally Kwesta s Ungudu with 3.2 million views and Babes Wodumo s Wololo with 3.4 million views make it at No7 and No8 respectively.SIYABONGA SITHOLEsiyabongas@thenewage.co.za